I personally want to say I appreciate the amount of support and feedback for this event. 

The question that always comes up is, "Why did @ladynate @faithnhustle and I start the Artists Town Hall?" The short answer is we saw a problem in Houston and created a solution. 

So many artists were complaining about things that could easily be fixed, but they didn't know who to go to for help. The Artists Town Hall is a place where you can ask questions to qualified experts and get answers that can help you grow your career. 

Use this event to network work with everyone on the panel. This is your opportunity as a manager, artists or industry professional to be in the room with some of the most qualified people in the music business.

20 things a personal manager can do. 
1. Develop a strategic career plan for the artist.
2. Provide guidance and mentorship for the artist's artistic and professional development.
3. Assist with branding, image development, and overall artist identity.
4. Coordinate and manage the artist's team, including musicians, stylists, and support staff.
5. Research industry trends, market demands, and emerging opportunities.
6. Cultivate and maintain relationships with industry professionals, including record label executives, A&R representatives, and booking agents.
7. Secure performance opportunities, such as gigs, showcases, and festivals.
8. Negotiate contracts, licensing agreements, and other business deals on behalf of the artist.
9. Advise on legal matters, including copyright, intellectual property, and contract law.
10. Provide financial guidance, budgeting support, and oversee royalty collections.
11. Collaborate with PR teams and marketing professionals to develop and execute effective promotional strategies.
12. Assist with social media management and online presence.
13. Advise on merchandise and merchandise sales strategies.
14. Coordinate and oversee the production and release of music projects, including album releases and singles.
15. Plan and manage tours, including logistics, travel arrangements, and budgeting.
16. Act as a liaison between the artist and record labels, publishers, agents, and other industry professionals.
17. Attend industry events, conferences, and networking opportunities on behalf of the artist.
18. Provide emotional support and serve as a trusted advisor to the artist.
19. Stay informed about industry regulations, trends, and changes that may impact the artist's career.
20. Continuously monitor and evaluate the artist's career progress, making adjustments and strategic shifts as needed.

When building a fan base, you must be consistently putting out music or videos. We live in a world where people have a short attention span, and they are always looking for what is next. Keep putting out music with a plan. You must have a plan of action for each song.
When building a fan base online, you must interact. Make people feel a part of your community. Until you reach Mainstream, you must engage with the people who will buy your music.

Collaboration is a powerful tool. Working with other artists introduces your music to their fans, and vice versa. It's an effective way to tap into new audiences while fostering a sense of unity within the music community.
